h packets (`011`, `013`, `030`) converge on **napi-rs / WASM / sidecar Rust interoperating with the existing TypeScript/Node MCP backend**, under **byte-for-byte determinism/parity** contracts (six-decimal scores, stable sort/tie-breaks). The Rust standard must be weighted to *that* reality, not a generic Rust styleguide.\n\n  Line 100: - Deep-dive the interop surface (napi-rs, wasm-bindgen/wasm-pack, cxx): boundary DTO stability, error propagation, copy vs zero-copy, build/packaging, and cross-platform native-ABI fragility.\n\n  Line 106: - Writing Rust, scaffolding a crate, or wiring napi-rs/WASM anywhere.\n\n  Line 151: - **SC-003**: The Rust standard is weighted to napi-rs/WASM interop + determinism parity, not a generic styleguide; each non-negotiable names the repo contract it protects.\n\n  Line 162: | Risk | Generic Rust styleguide that ignores the interop reality | Misfit standard, low value | Framing invariant forces napi-rs/WASM/sidecar + determinism weighting every round |\n\n  Line 183: 4. **A4 — FFI/interop (the load-bearing angle).** `napi-rs` (Node addon), `wasm-bindgen`/`wasm-pack` (WASM), `cxx`: boundary DTO stability, error propagation across the boundary, copy vs zero-copy, panic-safety, and build/packaging (`prebuildify`, cross-platform, native-ABI fragility). `[SOURCE: url]`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-code/018-rust-standards-for-code-opencode/001-research/plan.md:\n  Line 50: Run one deep-research lineage of up to 10 rounds with GPT-5.6-sol (high, fast) via `cli-opencode`, across three thrusts: (A) external Rust best practices weighted to napi-rs/WASM interop + determinism parity, (B) our skill/standard conventions and the new-language registration + drift-guard mechanics, and (C) the existing code-opencode language trios as the structural template. Synthesize a Rust standard (trio + checklist content) and an exact upgrade manifest for phase 002. Research-only: no Rust is written a