{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784521176644,"sessionID":"ses_082429307ffehbt81HPaprV8I0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_JjYHA8KNDwIJRB3qi6C3jPYc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style-guide/interop-model.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style-guide/interop-model.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Model & Boundary Types\n3: description: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Model & Boundary Types.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"rust typescript interop model boundary types\"\n6:   - \"rust interop model\"\n7:   - \"rust style guidance\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: implementation\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: ---\n12: \n13: # Rust/TypeScript Interop — Model & Boundary Types\n14: \n15: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n20: \n21: ### Purpose\n22: \n23: Provides focused Rust guidance for rust/typescript interop — model & boundary types in the OpenCode development environment.\n24: \n25: ### When to Use\n26: \n27: - Implementing or reviewing Rust code covered by this topic\n28: - Preserving TypeScript interoperability and deterministic behavior\n29: - Applying the corresponding Rust standards at an implementation boundary\n30: \n31: ---\n32: \n33: ## 2. RUST/TYPESCRIPT INTEROP AND COEXISTENCE\n34: \n35: Rust supplements the existing TypeScript/Node backend. It does not replace transport ownership or redefine public MCP behavior.\n36: \n37: ### Responsibility Split\n38: \n39: | TypeScript/Node Owns | Rust Owns |\n40: |----------------------|-----------|\n41: | MCP transport and tool schemas | Measured compute kernels |\n42: | Daemon and CLI wiring | Validation internal to a kernel |\n43: | Feature flags and fallback selection | Deterministic ranking and hashing |\n44: | Public request routing | Canonical numeric operations |\n45: | Compatibility orchestration | Transport-neutral domain types |\n46: | JavaScript fallback behavior | Narrow napi-rs/WASM/sidecar adapters |\n47: \n48: Move code into Rust only when measurement justifies the added boundary and build complexity.\n49: \n50: ### Pure Core and Thin Adapters\n51: \n52: The core API accepts transport-neutral, owned inputs and returns transport-neutral, owned outputs.\n53: \n54: ```rust\n55: #![forbid(unsafe_code)]\n56: \n57: use thiserror::Error;\n58: \n59: #[derive(Debug, Clone)]\n60: pub struct Candidate {\n61:     pub id: String,\n62:     pub score: f64,\n63: }\n64: \n65: #[derive(Debug, Clone)]\n66: pub struct RankedCandidate {\n67:     pub id: String,\n68:     pub score: f64,\n69: }\n70: \n71: #[derive(Debug, Error)]\n72: pub enum CoreError {\n73:     #[error(\"candidate identifier must not be empty\")]\n74:     EmptyIdentifier,\n75: \n76:     #[error(\"candidate score must be finite\")]\n77:     NonFiniteScore,\n78: }\n79: \n80: pub fn rank_candidates(\n81:     candidates: Vec<Candidate>,\n82: ) -> Result<Vec<RankedCandidate>, CoreError> {\n83:     let mut ranked = candidates\n84:         .into_iter()\n85:         .map(|candidate| {\n86:             if candidate.id.is_empty() {\n87:                 return Err(CoreError::EmptyIdentifier);\n88:             }\n89: \n90:             if !candidate.score.is_finite() {\n91:                 return Err(CoreError::NonFiniteScore);\n92:             }\n93: \n94:             Ok(RankedCandidate {\n95:                 id: candidate.id,\n96:                 score: candidate.score,\n97:             })\n98:         })\n99:         .collect::<Result<Vec<_>, _>>()?;\n100: \n101:     ranked.sort_by(|left, right| {\n102:         right\n103:             .score\n104:             .total_cmp(&left.score)\n105:             .then_with(|| left.id.cmp(&right.id))\n106:     });\n107: \n108:     Ok(ranked)\n109: }\n110: ```\n111: \n112: The adapter performs DTO conversion and stable error mapping, not ranking logic.\n113: \n114: ### Owned Versus Borrowed Boundary Types\n115: \n116: Export owned, materialized values:\n117: \n118: - `String`\n119: - `Vec<T>`\n120: - Fixed-width integers such as `u32`, `i64`, and `u64`\n121: - `f64` only with explicit finite-value and numeric-parity handling\n122: - `bool`\n123: - Passive boundary structs\n124: - `Result<OwnedOutput, BoundaryError>`\n125: \n126: Do not export:\n127: \n128: - `&str`\n129: - `&[T]`\n130: - `Cow<'a, T>`\n131: - Public lifetime parameters\n132: - Iterators\n133: - Internal graph references\n134: - Core builders\n135: - Type-state objects\n136: - `usize` or `isize`\n137: \n138: Borrow inside the core:\n139: \n140: ```rust\n141: fn canonical_identifier(namespace: &str, name: &str) -> String {\n142:     format!(\"{namespace}:{name}\")\n143: }\n144: ```\n145: \n146: Materialize at the boundary:\n147: \n148: ```rust\n149: #[derive(Debug)]\n150: struct IdentifierRequest {\n151:     namespace: String,\n152:     name: String,\n153: }\n154: \n155: fn handle_identifier(request: IdentifierRequest) -> String {\n156:     canonical_identifier(&request.namespace, &request.name)\n157: }\n158: ```\n159: \n160: ### Buffer Ownership\n161: \n162: JavaScript-owned memory MUST be copied before asynchronous or cross-thread work unless a reviewed ownership protocol proves exclusive access for the full operation.\n163: \n164: ```rust\n165: fn prepare_async_input(input: &[u8]) -> Vec<u8> {\n166:     // The worker receives owned bytes because JavaScript may mutate or release\n167:     // the source buffer after this synchronous boundary call returns.\n168:     input.to_vec()\n169: }\n170: ```\n171: \n172: Zero-copy napi-rs or WASM views are synchronous optimization exceptions. They require:\n173: \n174: - Benchmark evidence\n175: - Explicit lifetime and mutation rules\n176: - Thread-affinity documentation\n177: - Safety review\n178: - Tests that challenge ownership assumptions\n179: \n180: ### Fixed-Width Integers\n181: \n182: Use fixed-width integers at every JavaScript-visible boundary.\n183: \n184: ```rust\n185: #[derive(Debug)]\n186: struct PaginationDto {\n187:     offset: u32,\n188:     limit: u32,\n189: }\n190: ```\n191: \n192: Never expose `usize` or `isize`; their width varies by target.\n193: \n194: Integers outside JavaScript's safe range require an explicitly versioned representation:\n195: \n196: ```rust\n197: #[derive(Debug)]\n198: struct LargeCounterDto {\n199:     decimal_value: String,\n200: }\n201: ```\n202: \n203: Use JavaScript `BigInt` only when both the binding technology and TypeScript contract explicitly require it.\n204: \n205: ### DTO Validation\n206: \n207: Boundary DTOs are passive and versioned. Convert them immediately into validated private-field core types.\n208: \n209: ```rust\n210: use thiserror::Error;\n211: \n212: #[derive(Debug)]\n213: struct SearchOptionsDto {\n214:     limit: u32,\n215:     minimum_score: f64,\n216: }\n217: \n218: #[derive(Debug)]\n219: struct SearchOptions {\n220:     limit: u32,\n221:     minimum_score: FiniteScore,\n222: }\n223: \n224: #[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy)]\n225: struct FiniteScore(f64);\n226: \n227: #[derive(Debug, Error)]\n228: enum OptionsError {\n229:     #[error(\"limit must be greater than zero\")]\n230:     EmptyLimit,\n231: \n232:     #[error(\"minimum score must be finite\")]\n233:     NonFiniteScore,\n234: }\n235: \n236: impl TryFrom<SearchOptionsDto> for SearchOptions {\n237:     type Error = OptionsError;\n238: \n239:     fn try_from(dto: SearchOptionsDto) -> Result<Self, Self::Error> {\n240:         if dto.limit == 0 {\n241:             return Err(OptionsError::EmptyLimit);\n242:         }\n243: \n244:         if !dto.minimum_score.is_finite() {\n245:             return Err(OptionsError::NonFiniteScore);\n246:         }\n247: \n248:         Ok(Self {\n249:             limit: dto.limit,\n250:             minimum_score: FiniteScore(dto.minimum_score),\n251:         })\n252:     }\n253: }\n254: ```\n255: \n256: ### `From` and `TryFrom`\n257: \n258: Use `From` only when conversion is:\n259: \n260: - Infallible\n261: - Lossless\n262: - Value-preserving\n263: - Unsurprising\n264: \n265: ```rust\n266: #[derive(Debug)]\n267: struct RankedCandidate {\n268:     id: String,\n269:     score: f64,\n270: }\n271: \n272: #[derive(Debug)]\n273: struct RankedCandidateDto {\n274:     id: String,\n275:     score: f64,\n276: }\n277: \n278: impl From<RankedCandidate> for RankedCandidateDto {\n279:     fn from(candidate: RankedCandidate) -> Self {\n280:         Self {\n281:             id: candidate.id,\n282:             score: candidate.score,\n283:         }\n284:     }\n285: }\n286: ```\n287: \n288: Use `TryFrom` for:\n289: \n290: - DTO validation\n291: - Finite-number checks\n292: - Integer narrowing\n293: - Enum parsing\n294: - Identifier normalization\n295: - Any conversion that can reject or alter invalid input\n296: \n297: ```rust\n298: #[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]\n299: enum MemoryState {\n300:     Active,\n301:     Archived,\n302: }\n303: \n304: #[derive(Debug, PartialEq, Eq)]\n305: struct StateParseError;\n306: \n307: impl TryFrom<&str> for MemoryState {\n308:     type Error = StateParseError;\n309: \n310:     fn try_from(value: &str) -> Result<Self, Self::Error> {\n311:         match value {\n312:             \"active\" => Ok(Self::Active),\n313:             \"archived\" => Ok(Self::Archived),\n314:             _ => Err(StateParseError),\n315:         }\n316:     }\n317: }\n318: ```\n319: \n320: Implement `From` or `TryFrom`, not `Into` or `TryInto`, directly.\n321: \n322: ### Enum Representation\n323: \n324: Use stable string discriminants or explicit numeric codes at the boundary. Never export incidental Rust ordinals.\n325: \n326: ```rust\n327: use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};\n328: \n329: #[derive(Debug, Deserialize, Serialize)]\n330: #[serde(rename_all = \"snake_case\")]\n331: enum MemoryTierDto {\n332:     Constitutional,\n333:     Working,\n334:     LongTerm,\n335: }\n336: ```\n337: \n338: Do not use `variant as u8` as a wire contract unless every numeric code is explicit and versioned.\n339: \n340: Use `#[non_exhaustive]` only when wildcard evolution is intentional. Adapter error mappings SHOULD remain exhaustive so new variants cannot silently receive the wrong JavaScript code.\n341: \n\n(End of file - total 341 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Model & Boundary Types\ndescription: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Model & Boundary Types.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"rust typescript interop model boundary types\"\n  - \"rust interop model\"\n  - \"rust style guidance\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Rust/TypeScript Interop — Model & Boundary Types\n\nFormatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style-guide/interop-model.md","text":"---\ntitle: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Model & Boundary Types\ndescription: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Model & Boundary Types.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"rust typescript interop model boundary types\"\n  - \"rust interop model\"\n  - \"rust style guidance\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Rust/TypeScript Interop — Model & Boundary Types\n\nFormatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nProvides focused Rust guidance for rust/typescript interop — model & boundary types in the OpenCode development environment.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Implementing or reviewing Rust code covered by this topic\n- Preserving TypeScript interoperability and deterministic behavior\n- Applying the corresponding Rust standards at an implementation boundary\n\n---\n\n## 2. RUST/TYPESCRIPT INTEROP AND COEXISTENCE\n\nRust supplements the existing TypeScript/Node backend. It does not replace transport ownership or redefine public MCP behavior.\n\n### Responsibility Split\n\n| TypeScript/Node Owns | Rust Owns |\n|----------------------|-----------|\n| MCP transport and tool schemas | Measured compute kernels |\n| Daemon and CLI wiring | Validation internal to a kernel |\n| Feature flags and fallback selection | Deterministic ranking and hashing |\n| Public request routing | Canonical numeric operations |\n| Compatibility orchestration | Transport-neutral domain types |\n| JavaScript fallback behavior | Narrow napi-rs/WASM/sidecar adapters |\n\nMove code into Rust only when measurement justifies the added boundary and build complexity.\n\n### Pure Core and Thin Adapters\n\nThe core API accepts transport-neutral, owned inputs and returns transport-neutral, owned outputs.\n\n```rust\n#![forbid(unsafe_code)]\n\nuse thiserror::Error;\n\n#[derive(Debug, Clone)]\npub struct Candidate {\n    pub id: String,\n    pub score: f64,\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug, Clone)]\npub struct RankedCandidate {\n    pub id: String,\n    pub score: f64,\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug, Error)]\npub enum CoreError {\n    #[error(\"candidate identifier must not be empty\")]\n    EmptyIdentifier,\n\n    #[error(\"candidate score must be finite\")]\n    NonFiniteScore,\n}\n\npub fn rank_candidates(\n    candidates: Vec<Candidate>,\n) -> Result<Vec<RankedCandidate>, CoreError> {\n    let mut ranked = candidates\n        .into_iter()\n        .map(|candidate| {\n            if candidate.id.is_empty() {\n                return Err(CoreError::EmptyIdentifier);\n            }\n\n            if !candidate.score.is_finite() {\n                return Err(CoreError::NonFiniteScore);\n            }\n\n            Ok(RankedCandidate {\n                id: candidate.id,\n                score: candidate.score,\n            })\n        })\n        .collect::<Result<Vec<_>, _>>()?;\n\n    ranked.sort_by(|left, right| {\n        right\n            .score\n            .total_cmp(&left.score)\n            .then_with(|| left.id.cmp(&right.id))\n    });\n\n    Ok(ranked)\n}\n```\n\nThe adapter performs DTO conversion and stable error mapping, not ranking logic.\n\n### Owned Versus Borrowed Boundary Types\n\nExport owned, materialized values:\n\n- `String`\n- `Vec<T>`\n- Fixed-width integers such as `u32`, `i64`, and `u64`\n- `f64` only with explicit finite-value and numeric-parity handling\n- `bool`\n- Passive boundary structs\n- `Result<OwnedOutput, BoundaryError>`\n\nDo not export:\n\n- `&str`\n- `&[T]`\n- `Cow<'a, T>`\n- Public lifetime parameters\n- Iterators\n- Internal graph references\n- Core builders\n- Type-state objects\n- `usize` or `isize`\n\nBorrow inside the core:\n\n```rust\nfn canonical_identifier(namespace: &str, name: &str) -> String {\n    format!(\"{namespace}:{name}\")\n}\n```\n\nMaterialize at the boundary:\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug)]\nstruct IdentifierRequest {\n    namespace: String,\n    name: String,\n}\n\nfn handle_identifier(request: IdentifierRequest) -> String {\n    canonical_identifier(&request.namespace, &request.name)\n}\n```\n\n### Buffer Ownership\n\nJavaScript-owned memory MUST be copied before asynchronous or cross-thread work unless a reviewed ownership protocol proves exclusive access for the full operation.\n\n```rust\nfn prepare_async_input(input: &[u8]) -> Vec<u8> {\n    // The worker receives owned bytes because JavaScript may mutate or release\n    // the source buffer after this synchronous boundary call returns.\n    input.to_vec()\n}\n```\n\nZero-copy napi-rs or WASM views are synchronous optimization exceptions. They require:\n\n- Benchmark evidence\n- Explicit lifetime and mutation rules\n- Thread-affinity documentation\n- Safety review\n- Tests that challenge ownership assumptions\n\n### Fixed-Width Integers\n\nUse fixed-width integers at every JavaScript-visible boundary.\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug)]\nstruct PaginationDto {\n    offset: u32,\n    limit: u32,\n}\n```\n\nNever expose `usize` or `isize`; their width varies by target.\n\nIntegers outside JavaScript's safe range require an explicitly versioned representation:\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug)]\nstruct LargeCounterDto {\n    decimal_value: String,\n}\n```\n\nUse JavaScript `BigInt` only when both the binding technology and TypeScript contract explicitly require it.\n\n### DTO Validation\n\nBoundary DTOs are passive and versioned. Convert them immediately into validated private-field core types.\n\n```rust\nuse thiserror::Error;\n\n#[derive(Debug)]\nstruct SearchOptionsDto {\n    limit: u32,\n    minimum_score: f64,\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug)]\nstruct SearchOptions {\n    limit: u32,\n    minimum_score: FiniteScore,\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy)]\nstruct FiniteScore(f64);\n\n#[derive(Debug, Error)]\nenum OptionsError {\n    #[error(\"limit must be greater than zero\")]\n    EmptyLimit,\n\n    #[error(\"minimum score must be finite\")]\n    NonFiniteScore,\n}\n\nimpl TryFrom<SearchOptionsDto> for SearchOptions {\n    type Error = OptionsError;\n\n    fn try_from(dto: SearchOptionsDto) -> Result<Self, Self::Error> {\n        if dto.limit == 0 {\n            return Err(OptionsError::EmptyLimit);\n        }\n\n        if !dto.minimum_score.is_finite() {\n            return Err(OptionsError::NonFiniteScore);\n        }\n\n        Ok(Self {\n            limit: dto.limit,\n            minimum_score: FiniteScore(dto.minimum_score),\n        })\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### `From` and `TryFrom`\n\nUse `From` only when conversion is:\n\n- Infallible\n- Lossless\n- Value-preserving\n- Unsurprising\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug)]\nstruct RankedCandidate {\n    id: String,\n    score: f64,\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug)]\nstruct RankedCandidateDto {\n    id: String,\n    score: f64,\n}\n\nimpl From<RankedCandidate> for RankedCandidateDto {\n    fn from(candidate: RankedCandidate) -> Self {\n        Self {\n            id: candidate.id,\n            score: candidate.score,\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nUse `TryFrom` for:\n\n- DTO validation\n- Finite-number checks\n- Integer narrowing\n- Enum parsing\n- Identifier normalization\n- Any conversion that can reject or alter invalid input\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]\nenum MemoryState {\n    Active,\n    Archived,\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug, PartialEq, Eq)]\nstruct StateParseError;\n\nimpl TryFrom<&str> for MemoryState {\n    type Error = StateParseError;\n\n    fn try_from(value: &str) -> Result<Self, Self::Error> {\n        match value {\n            \"active\" => Ok(Self::Active),\n            \"archived\" => Ok(Self::Archived),\n            _ => Err(StateParseError),\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nImplement `From` or `TryFrom`, not `Into` or `TryInto`, directly.\n\n### Enum Representation\n\nUse stable string discriminants or explicit numeric codes at the boundary. Never export incidental Rust ordinals.\n\n```rust\nuse serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};\n\n#[derive(Debug, Deserialize, Serialize)]\n#[serde(rename_all = \"snake_case\")]\nenum MemoryTierDto {\n    Constitutional,\n    Working,\n    LongTerm,\n}\n```\n\nDo not use `variant as u8` as a wire contract unless every numeric code is explicit and versioned.\n\nUse `#[non_exhaustive]` only when wildcard evolution is intentional. Adapter error mappings SHOULD remain exhaustive so new variants cannot silently receive the wrong JavaScript code.\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":341,"totalLines":341,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style-guide/interop-model.md","time":{"start":1784521176514,"end":1784521176642}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_010b440fd6a3e060016a5da1d85fb08191babfac6faa6cea52"}},"id":"prt_f7dc035c0001ciZ0f5emN9flnR","sessionID":"ses_082429307ffehbt81HPaprV8I0","messageID":"msg_f7dbff3510017Y2IIRsVHQuUUC"}}
