{"type":"text","timestamp":1784521922262,"sessionID":"ses_082429307ffehbt81HPaprV8I0","part":{"id":"prt_f7dcb9307001XXo2JpWPBNHrji","messageID":"msg_f7dcb685e001HTGdrxNnC6bcmR","sessionID":"ses_082429307ffehbt81HPaprV8I0","type":"text","text":"Iteration 1 passed the mechanical route-proof gate and established a useful threshold: exact search remains baseline through 10x, while HNSW becomes a benchmark candidate only around 100x and custom Rust only for unavailable capabilities such as filter-aware ANN. The reducer is now advancing focus to indexing and embedding automation.","time":{"start":1784521921287,"end":1784521922259},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0ffbc8a548cbd1ea016a5da4c1447081918e44d333f99c005c","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784521923911,"sessionID":"ses_082429307ffehbt81HPaprV8I0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_OUILTJLXHaZkLKRU7SVhIYFU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/deep-research-strategy.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/deep-research-strategy.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Deep Research Strategy: Rust Opportunities for the Styles Database\n2: \n3: ## 2. TOPIC\n4: Identify which new features, optimizations, automations, and integrations a Rust component could add or improve for the sk-design styles database, explicitly not a like-for-like rewrite.\n5: \n6: <!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n7: ## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n8: - [ ] Which vector-search architecture, if any, unlocks meaningful capability at 1,290, 10x, and 100x bundles: in-process HNSW/IVF, a SQLite loadable extension, WASM, or an existing native addon?\n9: - [ ] Which indexing and embedding automations become materially better with Rust: parallel streaming ingestion, incremental content hashing, local model inference, file watching, and content-addressed caches?\n10: - [ ] Which new visual/style-analysis features are practical: screenshot palette and spacing extraction, perceptual hashing, layout fingerprints, and multimodal embeddings?\n11: - [ ] Is a shared Rust search core across sk-design, system-code-graph, and Spec Kit Memory valuable enough to justify contract, release, and ownership coordination?\n12: - [ ] Which opportunities clear the repository's residency, materiality, and scale gates today versus only under measured growth, and what phased adoption preserves TS ownership and exact oracle parity?\n13: \n14: <!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n15: \n16: ## 4. NON-GOALS\n17: - Do not propose porting FTS5 or SQLite storage already executed natively by `node:sqlite`.\n18: - Do not propose a like-for-like port of the current cosine loop, weighted RRF, or regex tokenizer.\n19: - Do not implement Rust or alter production styles-database code.\n20: - Do not claim speedups from language choice without locating the compute residency and scale threshold.\n21: \n22: ## 5. STOP CONDITIONS\n23: - Complete exactly 10 evidence iterations; convergence before iteration 10 is telemetry only.\n24: - Synthesize a ranked opportunity matrix and phased adoption path after iteration 10.\n25: - Stop early only for unrecoverable state corruption or a write-boundary violation.\n26: \n27: <!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n28: ## 6. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n29: [None yet]\n30: \n31: <!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n32: \n33: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n34: <!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n35: ## 7. WHAT WORKED\n36: [None yet]\n37: \n38: <!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n39: \n40: <!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n41: ## 8. WHAT FAILED\n42: [None yet]\n43: \n44: <!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n45: \n46: <!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n47: ## 9. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n48: [No exhausted approach categories yet]\n49: \n50: <!-- /ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n51: \n52: <!-- ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n53: ## 10. RULED OUT DIRECTIONS\n54: [None yet]\n55: \n56: <!-- /ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n57: \n58: <!-- ANCHOR:divergence-frontier -->\n59: ## 10A. SATURATED DIRECTIONS AND DIVERGENCE FRONTIER\n60: - Completed pivots: 0\n61: - Failed pivots: 0\n62: - Audited overrides: 0\n63: - Saturated: none yet\n64: - Pivot lineage: none yet\n65: - Remaining frontier: none recorded\n66: \n67: <!-- /ANCHOR:divergence-frontier -->\n68: \n69: <!-- ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n70: ## 11A. CARRIED-FORWARD OPEN QUESTIONS\n71: - Is a shared Rust search core worth cross-system coordination? (iteration 1)\n72: - Which visual and multimodal analysis features are practical? (iteration 1)\n73: - Which complete opportunity set clears residency, materiality, and scale gates? (iteration 1)\n74: - Can the existing generation publication model atomically publish an external HNSW index with the SQLite database, or does it require a new manifest contract? (iteration 1)\n75: - Which indexing and embedding automations materially improve with Rust? (iteration 1)\n76: - What measured p50/p95 query latency, vector dimension, eligible-row distribution, and query rate trigger the 10x or 100x migration gate? (iteration 1)\n77: \n78: <!-- /ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n79: \n80: <!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n81: ## 11. NEXT FOCUS\n82: What measured p50/p95 query latency, vector dimension, eligible-row distribution, and query rate trigger the 10x or 100x migration gate?\n83: \n84: <!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n85: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n86: \n87: ## 12. KNOWN CONTEXT\n88: - The current lexical lane runs as FTS5 SQL through `node:sqlite`; vector rows are loaded from SQLite and only cosine scoring/sorting occurs in JS. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:200-249]\n89: - Weighted RRF is a deterministic map-and-sort over already-ranked candidate lists. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:252-283]\n90: - Vector embedding work already has an incremental queue, retrieval-hash cache, bounded retries, and lexical fallback semantics. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/vectors.mjs:78-313]\n91: - Rust must remain a pure core behind thin adapters; TypeScript owns transport, feature flags, fallback selection, and public routing. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style-guide/interop-model.md:33-52]\n92: - The active charter fixes the current corpus at about 1,290 bundles and forbids a straight rewrite. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/spec.md:48-76]\n93: - `resource-map.md` was not present at init; skipping the coverage-map preload.\n94: \n95: ### Bounded Context Snapshot\n96: - Source pointers: `styles/_db/retrieval.mjs`, `styles/_db/vectors.mjs`, the styles schema/build adapters, and the Rust interop/parity standards.\n97: - Reuse candidates: retrieval hashes, embedding profiles, queue retry semantics, generation publication, weighted-RRF oracle, and legacy/shadow/persistent adapter selection.\n98: - Integration points: query vector lane, vector projection build, style corpus ingestion, screenshot/provenance records, code graph, and memory retrieval systems.\n99: - Constraints: packet-local writes only; no production edits; no speed claim without residency and scale evidence.\n100: \n101: ## 13. RESEARCH BOUNDARIES\n102: - Max iterations: 10\n103: - Convergence threshold: 0.05, telemetry only before the hard cap\n104: - Stop policy: max-iterations\n105: - Per-iteration budget: 12 tool calls, 10 minutes\n106: - Progressive synthesis: true\n107: - Current generation: 1\n108: - Started: 2026-07-20T04:20:12Z\n\n(End of file - total 108 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Deep Research Strategy: Rust Opportunities for the Styles Database\n\n## 2. TOPIC\nIdentify which new features, optimizations, automations, and integrations a Rust component could add or improve for the sk-design styles database, explicitly not a like-for-like rewrite.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n- [ ] Which vector-search architecture, if any, unlocks meaningful capability at 1,290, 10x, and 100x bundles: in-process HNSW/IVF, a SQLite loadable extension, WASM, or an existing native addon?\n- [ ] Which indexing and embedding automations become materially better with Rust: parallel streaming ingestion, incremental content hashing, local model inference, file watching, and content-addressed caches?\n- [ ] Which new visual/style-analysis features are practical: screenshot palette and spacing extraction, perceptual hashing, layout fingerprints, and multimodal embeddings?\n- [ ] Is a shared Rust search core across sk-design, system-code-graph, and Spec Kit Memory valuable enough to justify contract, release, and ownership coordination?\n- [ ] Which opportunities clear the repository's residency, materiality, and scale gates today versus only under measured growth, and what phased adoption preserves TS ownership and exact oracle parity?\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n\n## 4. NON-GOALS\n- Do not propose porting FTS5 or SQLite storage already executed natively by `node:sqlite`.\n- Do not propose a like-for-like port of the current cosine loop, weighted RRF, or regex tokenizer.\n- Do not implement Rust or alter production styles-database code.\n- Do not claim speedups from language choice without locating the compute residency and scale threshold.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/deep-research-strategy.md","text":"# Deep Research Strategy: Rust Opportunities for the Styles Database\n\n## 2. TOPIC\nIdentify which new features, optimizations, automations, and integrations a Rust component could add or improve for the sk-design styles database, explicitly not a like-for-like rewrite.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n- [ ] Which vector-search architecture, if any, unlocks meaningful capability at 1,290, 10x, and 100x bundles: in-process HNSW/IVF, a SQLite loadable extension, WASM, or an existing native addon?\n- [ ] Which indexing and embedding automations become materially better with Rust: parallel streaming ingestion, incremental content hashing, local model inference, file watching, and content-addressed caches?\n- [ ] Which new visual/style-analysis features are practical: screenshot palette and spacing extraction, perceptual hashing, layout fingerprints, and multimodal embeddings?\n- [ ] Is a shared Rust search core across sk-design, system-code-graph, and Spec Kit Memory valuable enough to justify contract, release, and ownership coordination?\n- [ ] Which opportunities clear the repository's residency, materiality, and scale gates today versus only under measured growth, and what phased adoption preserves TS ownership and exact oracle parity?\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n\n## 4. NON-GOALS\n- Do not propose porting FTS5 or SQLite storage already executed natively by `node:sqlite`.\n- Do not propose a like-for-like port of the current cosine loop, weighted RRF, or regex tokenizer.\n- Do not implement Rust or alter production styles-database code.\n- Do not claim speedups from language choice without locating the compute residency and scale threshold.\n\n## 5. STOP CONDITIONS\n- Complete exactly 10 evidence iterations; convergence before iteration 10 is telemetry only.\n- Synthesize a ranked opportunity matrix and phased adoption path after iteration 10.\n- Stop early only for unrecoverable state corruption or a write-boundary violation.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n## 6. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n[None yet]\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n## 7. WHAT WORKED\n[None yet]\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n## 8. WHAT FAILED\n[None yet]\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n## 9. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n[No exhausted approach categories yet]\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n## 10. RULED OUT DIRECTIONS\n[None yet]\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:divergence-frontier -->\n## 10A. SATURATED DIRECTIONS AND DIVERGENCE FRONTIER\n- Completed pivots: 0\n- Failed pivots: 0\n- Audited overrides: 0\n- Saturated: none yet\n- Pivot lineage: none yet\n- Remaining frontier: none recorded\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:divergence-frontier -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n## 11A. CARRIED-FORWARD OPEN QUESTIONS\n- Is a shared Rust search core worth cross-system coordination? (iteration 1)\n- Which visual and multimodal analysis features are practical? (iteration 1)\n- Which complete opportunity set clears residency, materiality, and scale gates? (iteration 1)\n- Can the existing generation publication model atomically publish an external HNSW index with the SQLite database, or does it require a new manifest contract? (iteration 1)\n- Which indexing and embedding automations materially improve with Rust? (iteration 1)\n- What measured p50/p95 query latency, vector dimension, eligible-row distribution, and query rate trigger the 10x or 100x migration gate? (iteration 1)\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n## 11. NEXT FOCUS\nWhat measured p50/p95 query latency, vector dimension, eligible-row distribution, and query rate trigger the 10x or 100x migration gate?\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n\n## 12. KNOWN CONTEXT\n- The current lexical lane runs as FTS5 SQL through `node:sqlite`; vector rows are loaded from SQLite and only cosine scoring/sorting occurs in JS. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:200-249]\n- Weighted RRF is a deterministic map-and-sort over already-ranked candidate lists. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:252-283]\n- Vector embedding work already has an incremental queue, retrieval-hash cache, bounded retries, and lexical fallback semantics. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/vectors.mjs:78-313]\n- Rust must remain a pure core behind thin adapters; TypeScript owns transport, feature flags, fallback selection, and public routing. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style-guide/interop-model.md:33-52]\n- The active charter fixes the current corpus at about 1,290 bundles and forbids a straight rewrite. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/spec.md:48-76]\n- `resource-map.md` was not present at init; skipping the coverage-map preload.\n\n### Bounded Context Snapshot\n- Source pointers: `styles/_db/retrieval.mjs`, `styles/_db/vectors.mjs`, the styles schema/build adapters, and the Rust interop/parity standards.\n- Reuse candidates: retrieval hashes, embedding profiles, queue retry semantics, generation publication, weighted-RRF oracle, and legacy/shadow/persistent adapter selection.\n- Integration points: query vector lane, vector projection build, style corpus ingestion, screenshot/provenance records, code graph, and memory retrieval systems.\n- Constraints: packet-local writes only; no production edits; no speed claim without residency and scale evidence.\n\n## 13. RESEARCH BOUNDARIES\n- Max iterations: 10\n- Convergence threshold: 0.05, telemetry only before the hard cap\n- Stop policy: max-iterations\n- Per-iteration budget: 12 tool calls, 10 minutes\n- Progressive synthesis: true\n- Current generation: 1\n- Started: 2026-07-20T04:20:12Z","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":108,"totalLines":108,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/deep-research-strategy.md","time":{"start":1784521923905,"end":1784521923910}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0ffbc8a548cbd1ea016a5da4c24074819180f6448fecfbad8e"}},"id":"prt_f7dcb96d40019SSpZyRKi8zUdC","sessionID":"ses_082429307ffehbt81HPaprV8I0","messageID":"msg_f7dcb685e001HTGdrxNnC6bcmR"}}
