{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784522901466,"sessionID":"ses_082429307ffehbt81HPaprV8I0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_mAHg5buXdXkKLW3S9ik8x54q","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/deep-research-strategy.md","offset":80,"limit":25},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/deep-research-strategy.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n80: - Which indexing and embedding automations become materially better with Rust? (iteration 3)\n81: - Can an external vector index or shared cache be atomically bound to the current generation pointer without a new manifest contract? (iteration 4)\n82: - What production arrival, facet-selectivity, cold-build stage, and embedding-drain measurements clear the staged gates? (iteration 4)\n83: - Which visual and multimodal analysis features are practical, and which can share the same resident local-model worker? (iteration 4)\n84: - Which complete opportunity set clears residency, materiality, and scale gates at current, 10x, and 100x scale? (iteration 4)\n85: - Is a shared Rust inference/search core worth cross-system contract and release coordination? (iteration 4)\n86: \n87: <!-- /ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n88: \n89: <!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n90: ## 11. NEXT FOCUS\n91: Is a shared Rust inference/search core worth cross-system contract and release coordination?\n92: \n93: <!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n94: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n95: \n96: ## 12. KNOWN CONTEXT\n97: - The current lexical lane runs as FTS5 SQL through `node:sqlite`; vector rows are loaded from SQLite and only cosine scoring/sorting occurs in JS. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:200-249]\n98: - Weighted RRF is a deterministic map-and-sort over already-ranked candidate lists. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:252-283]\n99: - Vector embedding work already has an incremental queue, retrieval-hash cache, bounded retries, and lexical fallback semantics. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/vectors.mjs:78-313]\n100: - Rust must remain a pure core behind thin adapters; TypeScript owns transport, feature flags, fallback selection, and public routing. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style-guide/interop-model.md:33-52]\n101: - The active charter fixes the current corpus at about 1,290 bundles and forbids a straight rewrite. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/spec.md:48-76]\n102: - `resource-map.md` was not present at init; skipping the coverage-map preload.\n103: \n104: ### Bounded Context Snapshot\n\n(Showing lines 80-104 of 117. Use offset=105 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- Which indexing and embedding automations become materially better with Rust? (iteration 3)\n- Can an external vector index or shared cache be atomically bound to the current generation pointer without a new manifest contract? (iteration 4)\n- What production arrival, facet-selectivity, cold-build stage, and embedding-drain measurements clear the staged gates? (iteration 4)\n- Which visual and multimodal analysis features are practical, and which can share the same resident local-model worker? (iteration 4)\n- Which complete opportunity set clears residency, materiality, and scale gates at current, 10x, and 100x scale? (iteration 4)\n- Is a shared Rust inference/search core worth cross-system contract and release coordination? (iteration 4)\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n## 11. NEXT FOCUS\nIs a shared Rust inference/search core worth cross-system contract and release coordination?\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n\n## 12. KNOWN CONTEXT\n- The current lexical lane runs as FTS5 SQL through `node:sqlite`; vector rows are loaded from SQLite and only cosine scoring/sorting occurs in JS. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:200-249]\n- Weighted RRF is a deterministic map-and-sort over already-ranked candidate lists. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:252-283]\n- Vector embedding work already has an incremental queue, retrieval-hash cache, bounded retries, and lexical fallback semantics. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/vectors.mjs:78-313]","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/deep-research-strategy.md","text":"- Which indexing and embedding automations become materially better with Rust? (iteration 3)\n- Can an external vector index or shared cache be atomically bound to the current generation pointer without a new manifest contract? (iteration 4)\n- What production arrival, facet-selectivity, cold-build stage, and embedding-drain measurements clear the staged gates? (iteration 4)\n- Which visual and multimodal analysis features are practical, and which can share the same resident local-model worker? (iteration 4)\n- Which complete opportunity set clears residency, materiality, and scale gates at current, 10x, and 100x scale? (iteration 4)\n- Is a shared Rust inference/search core worth cross-system contract and release coordination? (iteration 4)\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n## 11. NEXT FOCUS\nIs a shared Rust inference/search core worth cross-system contract and release coordination?\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n\n## 12. KNOWN CONTEXT\n- The current lexical lane runs as FTS5 SQL through `node:sqlite`; vector rows are loaded from SQLite and only cosine scoring/sorting occurs in JS. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:200-249]\n- Weighted RRF is a deterministic map-and-sort over already-ranked candidate lists. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:252-283]\n- Vector embedding work already has an incremental queue, retrieval-hash cache, bounded retries, and lexical fallback semantics. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/vectors.mjs:78-313]\n- Rust must remain a pure core behind thin adapters; TypeScript owns transport, feature flags, fallback selection, and public routing. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style-guide/interop-model.md:33-52]\n- The active charter fixes the current corpus at about 1,290 bundles and forbids a straight rewrite. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/spec.md:48-76]\n- `resource-map.md` was not present at init; skipping the coverage-map preload.\n\n### Bounded Context Snapshot","lineStart":80,"lineEnd":104,"totalLines":117,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/deep-research-strategy.md","time":{"start":1784522901460,"end":1784522901465}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_02e06f02c4dcaef8016a5da89435f08191bd114ca40c2a67f3"}},"id":"prt_f7dda8311001nbLbpKzSMOkk3R","sessionID":"ses_082429307ffehbt81HPaprV8I0","messageID":"msg_f7dda7443001gpwrArkMCnliML"}}
